There is nothing that matches a meal at Danko's - you need to fast for a day before going, and make sure you have nothing to do right before or after your reservation, because going here is an event in itself. I've been to GD's three times over the last five years. Of course the food and service are excellent but, given the level at which this place portends to playing at, I think you have to expect a little more than that. I find the menu often lacks real creativity (Atelier Crenn, for example, is significantly stronger there) and has none of the charm that other high-end SF menus offer (consider Keiko's on Nob Hill). The decor seems confused - it's part stuffy and formal, but part modern ... ends up coming off like a more expensive version of a Marriott entrance area. The service is also a little too all-knowing - feels fake and appears to assume that you could only possibly be dining due to a special occasion (vs being someone who enjoys excellent food). And, last but not least, the crowd that it tends to draw can be appalling. I've experienced badly-behaved sugar daddies with their youthful playthings, some guy who obviously thought it was the epitome of cool to wear a baseball cap to a fine dining restaurant and someone who felt the need to pronounce everything very, VERY loudly in a bad French accent. Like I say, it's obviously an excellent restaurant and if you're someone who normally dines at a lower level and wants a fancy 'event' experience, it's going to do fine for you. If, on the other hand, you're someone who dines as a hobby and is, perhaps, more familiar with the New York or London scenes, for example, you're going to be a bit disappointed. Look no further, in fact, than the Michelin rating ... it's a One Star. Don't go expecting a Two or Three Star experience. If you know and enjoy the difference, save your money for Coi, Crenn or, make the trip and visit Mecca (aka The Laundry).

I went here for a birthday dinner and was excited to finally get a chance to try this place. The food was great and lived up to its reputation. A lot of reviews laud the service at Gary Danko and I expected really great service here. For the most part it was perfectly polite, but you could tell our waiter was rushing through his part and just reciting his words. He was fairly disinterested throughout the dinner. This was our first time here, and when we first sat down and looked through the menu, our waiter shortly appeared and abruptly asked what we wanted without asking us if we had any questions. We were a little thrown off and had to ask him to explain the menu and how it works. Two of us ordered the cheese course, I was at one side of the round table and the other was on the opposite side with a seat between us. When the waiter rolled out the cart, he started explaining it and then realized I had the course as well. The person sitting directly next to me had left to go to the restroom, so the waiter asked me to "scoot" one chair down because he claimed he wouldn't be able to fit the cart on my side of the table to explain it to me. I did so, since I didn't want to make a big deal out of this and he was obviously impatient. While he was going through the different types of cheeses at warp speed, another waiter brought a chocolate soufflÃ© dessert and broke it open and poured in the chocolate sauce that the person whose seat I was in, ordered. Clearly he thought I was the person who ordered it since I had "scooted" over, but it really should not have been served until the actual person who ordered it was back in his seat. All these are small things that you probably wouldn't notice at another restaurant, but at a Michelin grade place you expect more. Often service is meant to elevate the dining experience and here it felt rushed and indifferent.
